{"cursor":"7074","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\nIn politics, a 'defector' is a person who gives up allegiance to one state in\nexchange for allegiance to another, in a way which is considered illegitimate by\nthe first state. More broadly, it involves abandoning a person, cause or\ndoctrine to which one is bound by some tie, as of allegiance or\nduty. http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/defection \"deÂ·fecÂ·tion [dih-fek-\nshuhn] noun (1.) desertion from allegiance, loyalty, duty, or the like;\napostasy: His defection to East Germany was regarded as treasonable. (2.)\nfailure; lack; loss: He was overcome by a sudden defection of courage.\"\nRetrieved 22MARCH2011. http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/defector\n\"deÂ·fecÂ·tor [dih-fek-ter] ânoun a person who defects from a cause, country,\nalliance, etc. Origin: 1655â65; ","linknr":188,"url":"Defection","recorded":1362563151,"links":26,"instances":[],"pdf":[],"categories":["Defectors|","Military terminology","Political terminology","Spies by role"],"headings":["International politics","Famous defectors","See also","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/41/Checkpoint_Charlie_Memorial.JPG/220px-Checkpoint_Charlie_Memorial.JPG","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[],"members":[],"related":["Politics","Allegiance","Religion","Sports_team","Political_party","Traitor","Checkpoint_Charlie","Citizenship","East_German","West_Germany","Exclusive_mandate","Berlin_Wall","Inner_German_border","German_Democratic_Republic","List_of_deaths_at_the_Berlin_Wall","Republikflucht","Wolf_B